	EnergyIRS Resumes Issuing Private Letter Rulings
On Section 29 Tax Credit for Synthetic Fuels

The Internal Revenue Service announced April 20 in Revenue Procedure 2001-30=
=20
that it will resume issuing private letter rulings on whether synthetic fuel=
s=20
produced from coal qualify for a tax credit under tax code Section 29.=20
Section 29 provides a credit for the production and sale of "qualified fuels=
"=20
produced from a nonconventional source, IRS said, including liquid, gaseous,=
=20
or solid synthetic fuels produced from coal or lignite. In Rev. Proc. 2000-4=
7=20
(209 DTR G-1, L-1, 10/27/00), IRS stopped issuing rulings under Section 29=20
because it said it was concerned that taxpayers claiming the credit were not=
=20
processing the coal in the manner intended by Congress.=20
IRS asked for information on the processes used to produce solid fuel for=20
which taxpayers claimed the credit. It received numerous comment letters,=20
many urging it to resume issuing rulings, others agreeing that some processe=
s=20
should not qualify for the credit.=20

Ruling Requirements

In Rev. Proc. 2001-30, IRS said it will issue a ruling on processes it had=20
approved prior to 2000. The production process must meet the following=20
requirements, IRS said:=20

substantially all of the coal used as feedstock must undergo a significant=20
chemical change;=20
the feedstock coal must consist entirely of coal fines or crushed coal=20
comprised of particles no larger than 1/8 inch;=20
the feedstock coal must be thoroughly mixed: (a) with styrene or other=20
monomers following an acid bath, (b) with quinoline or other organic resin=20
and left to cure for several days, (c) with ultra heavy hydrocarbons, or (d)=
=20
with an aluminum and/or magnesium silicate binder after being heated to a=20
minimum temperature of 500 degrees Fahrenheit; and=20
the treatment method must involve elevated temperature and pressure that=20
results in briquettes, pellets, or an extruded fuel product or the taxpayer=20
may represent that the omission of these procedures will not significantly=20
increase the production output of the facility.

The revenue procedure applies to both pending and future ruling requests.=20
Rev. Proc. 2001-30 will be published in Internal Revenue Bulletin 2001-19,=20
dated May 7.=20
